Here is a sample C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    string wordToCount, wordToCheck;
    int count = 0;
    ifstream infile("textfile.txt");

    if (!infile) {
        cout << "File not found." << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    while (getline(infile, wordToCount)) {
        cout << wordToCount << endl;
        if (wordToCheck.find(wordToCount)!= string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    cout << "The word " << wordToCheck << " has been found " << count << " times." << endl;
    infile.close();
    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we use `getline` function from the `iostream` library to read each line into the `wordToCount` string variable. Then we output the `wordToCount` to the console, compare it with the word to be counted using `std::string::find` function, and increment the `count` variable accordingly. After reading all the lines of the file, we output the total count of the word to be found. Finally, we close the file with `infile.close()` function.

